Tachyon Condensation and Spacetime Decay 
The technique of in obtaining the orbifold theory from
the  world-volume theory of the parent brane-probe
is standard. Indeed the methodology of generalising
 depends
purely on the group theory of  and not limited to whether
the orbifold has Calabi-Yau resolution, whence it can be readily
applied here to obtain the resulting theory. The matter content
of course, is simply the McKay quiver associated to .
We need to be careful that since we are no longer protected by
supersymmetry we need to construct (generically quite) different
quivers for the fermions and the bosons (cf. ).

A quintessential idea of is that turning on marginal
or tachyonic deformations in the twisted sectors of the orbifold
theory induces partial resolutions of the initial non-SUSY
singularity. The process can be applied consecutively, each
stage being a -blowup. In other words, the stepwise
tachyonic condensation process corresponds precisely, in the
 example, to the Hirzebruch-Jung resolution 
outlined in Jung .

As we proceed in this decay of spacetime  where the very topology
of the singular spacetime changes, the symmetry of the theory
subsequently
changes. At each stage of the decay
we should be careful to preserve the quantum
symmetry of the theory while turning on VEV's of tachyons.
Turning on VEV's to break symmetry is of course nothing
but the Higgsing procedure. Indeed, in the case of the supersymmetric
quiver theories, especially the toric ones, such Higgsing procedures
can be systematically studied via the tuning of 
Fayet-Illiopoulos parametres 
and so-called Inverse Algorithm.

The  worldsheet CFT provides the link to study the
decay process from a geometric point of view. We can parametrise
the  by the chiral superfields  corresponding
to the coo rdinates . Then expanding into components
 (for 
),
we can bosonise the fermions as . 
Subsequently, defining






