The Classification of the Discrete Finite Subgroups of  
Having refreshed the readers' minds and motivated their hearts
on the interesting physics of
tachyon condensation on the non-supersymmetric orbifold
, one task is immediate. Can we perform a
similar analysis to all the non-SUSY orbifolds of ? This seems
to require a classification of the discrete finite subgroups of
. At first glance this may appear to be a rather intractable problem
because we seem to have the liberty to quotient  by any finite
group which affords a two-dimensional irreducible representation,
the list of which is certainly overwhelming. In what follows however
we shall see that it in fact suffices to consider what are known as small groups  and our candidate pool reduces considerably.

As in, we for the convenience of the readers leave a 
review on some rudiments to Appendix A.
The subject of  quotients dates back
as early as the sixties when Satakefirst introduced V-manifolds (or
what has today become known as orbifolds in the string theory
literature). 
Inspired by the extensive (and still ongoing) programme of the
study of resolutions of quotient singularities, the classification
of  orbifolds took form in.
To a comprehensive presentation in and especially
in is the reader referred.

Before we proceed however, some preliminary technicalities should be
addressed. To these we now briefly turn.

Small Groups and Quotient Singularities 
As we are dealing with quotients by the general linear
group, we are addressing the most general type of orbifold
singularities. As mentioned above, 
in principle, there should be a myriad of such
objects since for , one seems to only need to have a 
group with an -dimensional irrep to form the quotient.
However, the situation is in fact far more restrictive.
We define the following:
 
A group  acting on 
is a reflection group  if it is generated by elements
 which fix a hyperplane in , i.e., the eigenvalues of
 are 1 of multiplicity  together with , some
root of unity. The complement thereof, i.e., a group which does not
contain any reflections is called a small group .

The following Theorems of Prill andtherefore narrow down our search considerably and make
the small groups the building blocks of our orbifolds.
 
Every quotient singularity is isomorphic to a quotient by a small
group .
Moreover, we need only consider equivalence classes under conjugation:
 
If  and  are small groups in  and 
, then  and  are conjugate
in . 
Therefore the classification of conjugacy classes of small groups
of  suffices the classification of all complex
quotient singularities.

