(a) differs markedly from (b) and is only a small subgraph thereof.
 


Whereas the mathematics is clear, the physics on the other hand
becomes very involved. Naively, we could perform a similar
routine
as in decayfrac  to study the partial resolution of  to one
of its
subgroups, say , and we would have the rather curious
process



where we end up with a longer sequence than we had stated with. The
reason
for this failure has to do with the
weakness of the McKay Correspondence in 
this situation and will be addressed in Section .
Furthermore it is not clear at all to what operators these blowup
modes should correspond.

Indeed, the careful analysis of required the one-one 
correspondence between the basis for the chiral ring of the worldsheet
CFT and the exceptional divisors of the resolution so that the
acquisition
of tachyon VEV's and deformations to the CFT may be completely
re-phrased in terms of the geometric resolution of the orbifold. 
This is true for
Abelian orbifolds and thus far only true in this case 
(cf. e.g. ). For non-Abelian quotients subtleties
arise
. The McKay quivers, in comparison with the fusion
graphs
of the corresponding orbifold CFT, needs artificial truncation, i.e.,
only subsectors of the generators of the chiral ring are in
correspondence
with some of the blowup modes of the orbifold. The identification of
which operators to which divisor would be a very interesting problem to
which our list above provides half of the story.



Tachyons, Orbifolds and McKay Correspondence 
We mentioned above that the subtleties involved in the analysis of
the general non-supersymmetric orbifold are related to the Mckay
Correspondence;
in this section let us see this in some detail.

The traditional McKay Correspondence dictates that
for the discrete finite subgroups of  (q.v. Section
),
the McKay quiver drawn for the defining 2-dimensional representation
as in tensor  is precisely the Dynkin diagram for the
(simply laced)  affine Lie groups , each corresponding
to
the finite group of the same name. The subsequent work on the
geometrisation
of this correspondence (cf.  for an excellent account)
hinges
on the fact that for , there is a one-one
correspondence between the conjugacy classes of  and the
exceptional 
divisors in the (minimal,
crepant) resolution  of :
conj () ^2 /  , 
SL(2; )  .
In particular, cor  implies that the number of  blowups
is equal to the number of conjugacy classes of , which in
turn,
by an elementary theorem on the representation of finite groups,
is equal to the number of irreducible representations of .
Therefore, the number of nodes in the McKay quiver each corresponds to
a  and the intersection matrix amongst the 's is the
adjacency matrix of the quiver. Hence we can re-phrase cor  as
irrep ^0() H^*(^2 /  , )
where the cohomology picks up the exceptional divisors which are
 curves and  means the non-trivial
irreducible representations of . 
The nodes of the quiver are usually labeled by the dimension of the
corresponding irrep, which coincides with the Coxeter number of the
associated Dynkin diagram. In summary, the McKay quiver, the minimal
resolution graph for the exceptional 's and the affine ADE
Dynkin diagrams are identical for .
Everything therefore fits nicely
for Calabi-Yau orbifolds in dimension two.

For higher dimensions, the correspondence weakens substantially; though
still shown to hold for Abelian quotients in dimension three
(cf. ),
the generic
group has been so far intractable. In terms of the physics, 
the nice work offor example, has discussed how in the open sector, the 
system
exhibits tachyon condensation on three-dimensional 
Calabi-Yau (i.e., )
orbifolds and how boundary CFT modes can be interpreted via the McKay 
correspondence from the derived category point of view.
Here we are dealing with another generalisation,
viz., non-Calabi-Yau orbifolds in dimension two and works by Ishii, 
Riemenschneider et al. shed some light.

A Mismatch 
First of all we can immediately see that there is a mismatch between
the conjugacy classes (irreps) and the exceptional divisors for 
. The number of nodes in f:A  is  which
is 
the number of terms in the continued fraction expansion of
;
however,
the number of conjugacy classes of this Abelian group is .
As another example, 
in f:A5E6 , (a) and (b) differ significantly: the
number of exceptional divisors is 4 while there are 35 conjugacy
classes
(irreps). Indeed one can see that this is the general pattern: instead
of
having cor , we now have
 Irrep () >  Exceptional Div (
^2 /   ), 
GL(2; )  .
This discrepancy of course shows up in the physics. The twisted
sector operators in the orbifold CFT are counted by the conjugacy
classes of the group (we can see this when
summing up the torus partition function). When we are dealing with
D-brane probes, the equivariant K-theory of the orbifold gives the
representation ring of  and so there are still enough distinct
D-branes at the orbifold point. However in the resolution of the
singularity, gl2-cor  means that there are not enough cycles
for the distinct D-branes to wrap. In a very nicely
detailed gauged linear sigma model analysis, has shown that
in the toric case (i.e., ), while  charges come
from the Hirzebruch-Jung resolution (Higgs branch), 
an extra set of  D-branes
lives on the Coulomb branch whereby conserving the total D-brane
charges.

We remark that this mismatch phenomenon is quite generic and
stands largely unresolved for arbitrary quotients.
It was pointed out inthat the ADE meta-pattern, ubiquitous in
various fields, seems to enjoy the specialty of Calabi-Yaus in
dimension two. Indeed as was shown in, attempts
to relate the chiral fusion ring and twisted sector operators
associated with blowups (i.e., the full geometrisation
of the orbifold conformal field theory), even in the Calabi-Yau
case for dimension 3 met similar mismatches as gl2-cor .
Graphical truncation of the quivers are needed and only subsets
of the chiral operators can be placed in correspondence with
either the representation ring of the group, or with
the exceptional divisors in the resolution.


Ishii's McKay Correspondence for  
For the general two-dimensional quotients
we should not be discouraged by the mismatch mentioned
above, and there is a
partial
remedy. For this we need to first turn to the work by Ito and Nakamura.
It is known that the symmetric orbifold,  where 
is
the symmetric group on  elements, has a smooth resolution, the
so-called
Hilbert Scheme of points on , denoted as Hilb. It
was 
realised in that if one took 
 and
,
and considered the -equivariant version of the said
resolution, one
in fact has
